Bubble sort: This is a simple sorting algorithm that works by repeatedly swapping adjacent elements if they are in the wrong order. It has a time complexity of O(n^2) and a space complexity of O(1).

Insertion sort: This is a sorting algorithm that works by repeatedly inserting elements into a sorted list until the entire list is sorted. It has a time complexity of O(n^2) and a space complexity of O(1).

Selection sort: This is a sorting algorithm that works by repeatedly selecting the minimum element in an unsorted sublist and swapping it with the first element in the sublist. It has a time complexity of O(n^2) and a space complexity of O(1).

Merge sort: This is a divide-and-conquer sorting algorithm that works by dividing a list into two halves, sorting the halves, and then merging them together. It has a time complexity of O(n log n) and a space complexity of O(n).

Quick sort: This is a divide-and-conquer sorting algorithm that works by selecting a pivot element and partitioning the list around the pivot. It has a time complexity of O(n log n) and a space complexity of O(n).

Heap sort: This is a sorting algorithm that works by building a heap data structure from the input list and then repeatedly removing the largest element from the heap until the entire list is sorted. It has a time complexity of O(n log n) and a space complexity of O(n).

